## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The entire preemptive-abort model is removed.

### Pattern classification

| API found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | **Timeout enforcement** | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Control flow** | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Continue after abort** | Remove — not needed with cooperative model |

### Migrated code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Task.Run + CancellationToken replaces manual Thread + Abort
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Run work on the thread pool; wait with cancellation support
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must respond to cancellation

The code above stops *waiting*, but the work keeps running on the thread pool. If `work` must actually **stop**, it needs to cooperate:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token inside their work:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is cooperative. If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion even after timeout. |
| **Forgetting `using` on CTS** | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable` — leaking it leaks timers. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking I/O won't respond** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read`, etc. ignore tokens. Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O overloads instead. |
| **Lost cleanup logic** | The old `catch (ThreadAbortException) { ResetAbort(); }` block may have contained cleanup — move it to `finally` or `CancellationToken.Register`. |

### What was removed and why

| Removed | Why |
|---------|-----|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool — more efficient |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `WaitAsync(token)` provides cancellable waiting |
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in modern .NET |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | No abort to reset — cooperative model doesn't need it |
